WHOLESALE DISTRIBUTION SERVICE RATE SCHEDULE CENTRAL MAINE POWER COMPANY
OPTIONAL TARGETED SERVICE RATE: B-ES GENERAL SERVICE - ENERGY STORAGE
AVAILABILITY
This Rate is available to customers with electric storage facility charging load and who meet the availability and character of service criteria listed under one of the following general service rate schedules on file with the Maine Public Service Commission ("MPUC"): Small General Service ("SGS"), Small General Service - Time of Use ("SGS-TOU"), Medium General Service - Primary ("MGS-P"), Medium General Service - Secondary ("MGS-S"), Medium General Service - Primary - Time of Use ("MGS-P-TOU"), Medium General Service - Secondary - Time of Use ("MGS-S-TOU"), Intermediate General Service - Primary - Time of Use ("IGS-P-TOU"), Intermediate General Service - Secondary - Time of Use ("IGS-S-TOU"), Large General Service - Primary - Time of Use ("LGS-P-TOU"), Large General Service - Secondary - Time of Use ("LGS-S-TOU"), Large General Service - Subtransmission - Time of Use ("LGS-ST-TOU"), or Large General Service - Transmission - Time of Use ("LGS-T-TOU"). Energy storage facilities shall mean resources capable of receiving electric energy from Central Maine Power Company's ("CMP") transmission and distribution system and storing the electric energy for release to CMP's system at a later time. Customers also must meet the eligibility criteria detailed below.
ELIGIBILITY CRITERIA
A. The charging load for a qualifying energy storage facility must be metered separately from all other electricity consumption at the customer's service location. The energy storage charging load must be reported under a separately identified regional network load that does not include station service load or any other load. Only the electricity consumption related to energy storage charging load is eligible to take service under this Rate.
B. The energy storage facility must provide one or more of the following services to ISO-New England: reactive power voltage support, operating reserves, regulation and frequency response, balancing energy supply and demand, or addressing a reliability concern. Energy storage facilities shall be considered to be balancing energy supply and demand when they are responding to ISO-New England dispatch instructions in the real-time energy market.
C. This Rate does not apply to customers taking short-term delivery service.
DEMAND
For customers with maximum measured non-coincident demands below 400 kW and taking service under a rate option that is not time-differentiated, the monthly non-coincident peak demand shall be the highest 15-minute integrated kW demand registered during the month as determined by the Company.
For customers taking service under time-differentiated rates, the monthly non-coincident peak demand for each period, on-peak or shoulder, shall be the highest 15-minute integrated kW demand registered in each period during the month as determined by the Company.
For all customers taking service under this Rate, the monthly coincident peak demand shall be the highest 15-minute integrated kW demand registered during the calendar month at the time of the Company's monthly system peak.

I. COMMON SERVICE PROVISIONS This Wholesale Distribution Service Tariff establishes the common delivery service provisions and rates for Distribution Customers participating in wholesale market transactions using Central Maine Power Companys (CMPs) Distribution System. CMP, as the Distribution Provider, will provide Distribution Service pursuant to the applicable terms and conditions contained in this Tariff and Service Agreement. The Tariff is applicable for the transportation of energy that is purchased by a Distribution Customer in the ISO-NE wholesale market and delivered from the ISO-NE market to the Distribution Customer using the Distribution Providers Distribution System. These services are intended for use by an Eligible Customer who will resell the energy back to the ISO-NE market in a wholesale sales transaction. Distribution Service shall be provided between the Distribution Providers interconnection with the Transmission System and the Distribution Customers interconnection with the Distribution Providers Distribution System. 1. Definitions 1.1 Ancillary Services: Those services as defined in the OATT that are necessary to support the transmission of electric capacity and energy from resources to loads while maintaining reliable operation of the New England Transmission System in accordance with Good Utility Practice. 1.2 B-CPT-W Eligible Customer: An Electric Storage Facility that exclusively self-dispatches to store electric energy for sale for resale in the New England wholesale energy market that is or will be directly interconnected with Central Maines Distribution System.
1.3 B-ESA Eligible Customer: An Electric Storage Facility that exclusively follows ISO-NE dispatch instructions to provide Ancillary Services that is or will be directly interconnected with Central Maines Distribution System. 1.4 Central Maine (or CMP): The Central Maine Power Company. 1.5 Commission: The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1.6 Demand Charge Rate: A per/kW rate for Distribution Service as set forth in Sections II and III of the Tariff. 1.7 Distribution Customer: Any Eligible Customer that (i) executes a Service Agreement or (ii) requests in writing that the Distribution Provider file with the Commission, a proposed unexecuted Service Agreement to receive Distribution Service pursuant to the terms of the Tariff or (iii) receives Distribution Service from Central Maine whose demand does not exceed 2000 kW. 1.8 Distribution Provider: Central Maine Power Company, the public utility that owns, controls, and operates facilities used for the distribution of electric energy and provides Distribution Service under the Tariff. 1.9 Distribution Service: The wholesale distribution service provided under the Tariff.
1.10 Distribution System: Those non-ISO-NE administered delivery facilities owned, controlled and operated by the Distribution Provider that are used to provide Distribution Service under the Tariff. 1.11 Electric Storage Facility: A storage facility that participates in the New England Markets as described in ISO-NEs market rules. 1.12 Eligible Customer: A B-CPT-W Eligible Customer or a B-ESA Eligible Customer. 1.13 End-Use Customer: A Central Maine customer that takes final delivery of electric power and does not resell the power. 1.14 Good Utility Practice: Any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather includes all acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region, including those practices required by Federal Power Act Section 215(a)(4). 1.15 ISO-NE: The New England Independent System Operator, or any successor organization or entity, responsible for the continued operation of the New England Control Area and the administration of the Tariff, subject to regulation by the Commission. ISO-NE is a nonprofit corporation that controls certain transmission facilities of all Participating TOs and dispatches certain generating units and loads. 1.16 ISO Tariff: The ISO New England Inc. Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff, as it may be modified from time to time, and accepted by the Commission. 1.17 Local Network Service (LNS): Local transmission service provided by Central Maine pursuant to Schedule 21 and Schedule 21-CMP. 1.18 New England Transmission System: The system of transmission facilities, including PTF and Non-PTF, under ISO-NEs operational jurisdiction. 1.19 Open Access Transmission Tariff (OATT): Section II of the ISO New England Inc. Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff, as it may be modified from time to time, and accepted by the Commission. 1.20 Participating Transmission Owner (TO): A transmission owner that is a party to the TOA. 1.21 Parties: The Distribution Provider and the Distribution Customer receiving service under the Tariff. 1.22 Pool Transmission Facility (PTF): The transmission facilities owned by PTOs which meet the criteria specified in the OATT. 1.23 Regional Network Service (RNS): The transmission service over the PTF described in the OATT.
1.24 Service Agreement: The initial agreement and any amendments or supplements thereto entered into by the Distribution Customer and the Distribution Provider for service under the Tariff. 1.25 Tariff: This Wholesale Distribution Access Tariff. 1.26 Transmission Operating Agreement (TOA): The Transmission Operating Agreement between and among ISO-NE and the PTOs, as amended and restated from time to time. 1.27 Transmission Service: The transmission service provided over PTF under the terms and conditions of the OATT, designated as Regional Network Service, and over Central Maines Local Network (Non-PTF), designated as Local Network Service or Local Point-To-Point Service that is provided pursuant to Schedule 21 and Schedule 21-CMP. 1.28 Transmission System: The facilities owned, controlled or operated by Central Maine that are used to provide Transmission Service under the OATT, Schedule 21 and Schedule 21-CMP. Central Maines Transmission System consists of two parts: (1) those transmission facilities which qualify as PTF in accordance with the OATT and (2) those remaining transmission facilities which constitute Central Maines Local Network. 2. Ancillary Services Ancillary Services are needed with Transmission Service to maintain reliability within the New England Control Area. Ancillary Services are not available in or through this Tariff. This Tariff does provide a wholesale distribution rate for Electric Storage Facilities interconnected to the Distribution System providing Ancillary Services to the ISO-NE wholesale market. 3. Billing and Payment 3.1 Billing Procedure Within a reasonable time after the first day of each month, Central Maine shall submit an invoice to the Distribution Customer for the charges for all services furnished under this Tariff during the preceding month. The invoice shall be paid by the Distribution Customer within ten (10) days of receipt. All payments shall be made, in accordance with the procedure specified by Central Maine in immediately available funds payable to Central Maine, or by wire transfer to a bank named by Central Maine. 3.2 Customer Default In the event the Distribution Customer fails, for any reason other than a billing dispute as described below, to make payment to Central Maine on or before the due date as described above, and such failure of payment is not corrected within thirty (30) calendar days after Central Maine notifies the Distribution Customer to cure such failure, or if the Distribution Customer violates any provision of this Tariff or its Service Agreement, a default by the Distribution Customer shall be deemed to exist. Upon the occurrence of a default, Central Maine may initiate a proceeding with the Commission to terminate service but shall not terminate service until the Commission so approves any such request. In the event of a billing dispute between Central Maine and the Distribution Customer, Central Maine will continue to provide service pursuant to the Tariff and any Service Agreement hereunder as long as the Distribution Customer (i) continues to make all payments not in dispute, and (ii) pays into an independent escrow account the portion of the invoice in dispute, pending resolution of such dispute. If the Distribution Customer fails to meet these two requirements for continuation of service, then Central Maine may provide notice to the Distribution Customer of its intention to suspend service in sixty (60) days, and may proceed with such suspension. 3.3 Rate Election A Distribution Customer taking service under this Tariff may elect to switch between the rates contained in this Tariff (i.e., the B-CPT-W rate and the B-ESA rate), provided the Distribution Customer meets the eligibility requirements of the rate. Switching between the rates may not be made at shorter intervals than twelve months. 4. Force Majeure and Indemnification 4.1 Force Majeure An event of Force Majeure means any act of God, labor disturbance, act of the public enemy, war, insurrection, riot, fire, storm or flood, explosion, breakage or accident to machinery or equipment, any Curtailment, any order, regulation or restriction imposed by a court or governmental military or lawfully established civilian authorities, or any other cause beyond a partys control. Neither Central Maine nor the Distribution Customer will be considered in default as to any obligation under or related to this Tariff if prevented from fulfilling the obligation due to an event of Force Majeure; provided that no event of Force Majeure shall excuse any payment obligation hereunder or under a Service Agreement. However, a party whose performance under or related to this Tariff is hindered by an event of Force Majeure shall make all reasonable efforts to perform its obligations under or related to this Tariff, and shall promptly notify Central Maine or the Distribution Customer, whichever is appropriate, of the commencement and end of each event of Force Majeure. 4.2 Indemnification The Distribution Customer shall at all times indemnify, defend, and save Central Maine harmless from, any and all damages, losses, claims, including claims and actions relating to injury to or death of any person or damage to property, demands, suits, recoveries, costs and expenses, court costs, attorney fees, and all other obligations by or to third parties, arising out of or resulting from Central Maines performance of its obligations under or related to this Tariff on behalf of the Distribution Customer or resulting from the Distribution Customers acts or omissions under or related to this Tariff, except to the extent that Central Maine is found liable for gross negligence or intentional wrongdoing. For the purposes of this Section, the term third parties includes without limitation, customers under the Tariff, ISO-NE and any other Transmission Owners. 4.3 Limitations of Liability Central Maine shall not be liable (whether based on contract, indemnification, warranty, tort, strict liability or otherwise) for money damages or other compensation to the Distribution Customer for actions or omissions by Central Maine in performing its obligations under or related to this Tariff, or any Service Agreement hereunder, except to the extent that Central Maine is found liable for gross negligence or intentional misconduct and, in which case, Central Maine shall be liable for only actual direct damages. To the extent the Distribution Customer has claims against Central Maine, the Distribution Customer may only look to the assets of Central Maine for the enforcement of such claims and may not seek to enforce any claims against the Affiliates of Central Maine or the respective directors, members, officers, employees or agents of Central Maine or any of its Affiliates who the Distribution Customer acknowledges and agrees have no personal or other liability for obligations of Central Maine by reason of their status as Affiliates or directors, members, officers, employees or agents of Central Maine or any of its Affiliates. In no event shall Central Maine be liable for any incidental, consequential, multiple, punitive, special, exemplary, or indirect damages, or loss of revenues or profits, attorneys fees or costs arising out of, or connected in any way with the performance or non-performance of this Tariff or any Service Agreement hereunder, even if such damages are foreseeable or the damaged party has advised Central Maine of the possibility of such damages and regardless of whether any such damages are deemed to result from the failure or inadequacy of any exclusive or other remedy. 4.4 Survival The provisions of this Section 4 survive termination or expiration of this Tariff or a Service Agreement hereunder. 5. Creditworthiness For the purpose of determining the ability of the Distribution Customer to meet its obligations related to service hereunder, Central Maine may require reasonable credit review procedures in accordance with Attachment L of Schedule 21-CMP, wherein Distribution Customer shall be treated as a Transmission Customer and often referred to as Customer for purposes of Attachment L. 6. Dispute Resolution Procedures 6.1 Internal Dispute Resolution Procedures Any dispute between a Distribution Customer and Central Maine involving Distribution Service under this Tariff (excluding applications for rate changes or other changes to this Tariff, or to any Service Agreement entered into under this Tariff, which shall be presented directly to the Commission for resolution) shall be referred to a designated senior representative of Central Maine and a senior representative of the Distribution Customer for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the dispute within thirty (30) days or such other period as the parties may agree upon by mutual agreement, such dispute may be submitted to mediation or arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth in Section I.6 of the ISO Tariff.
6.2 Rights Under the Federal Power Act Nothing in this section shall restrict the rights of any party to file a complaint with the Commission or seek any other available remedy under relevant provisions of the Federal Power Act. 7. Governing Law Except as otherwise provided by federal law, this Tariff shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the state of Maine.

I. COMMON SERVICE PROVISIONS This Wholesale Distribution Service Tariff establishes the common delivery service provisions and rates for Distribution Customers participating in wholesale market transactions using Central Maine Power Companys (CMPs) Distribution System. CMP, as the Distribution Provider, will provide Distribution Service pursuant to the applicable terms and conditions contained in this Tariff and Service Agreement. The Tariff is applicable for the transportation of energy that is purchased by a Distribution Customer in the ISO-NE wholesale market and delivered from the ISO-NE market to the Distribution Customer using the Distribution Providers Distribution System. These services are intended for use by an Eligible Customer who will resell the energy back to the ISO-NE market in a wholesale sales transaction. Distribution Service shall be provided between the Distribution Providers interconnection with the Transmission System and the Distribution Customers interconnection with the Distribution Providers Distribution System. 1. Definitions 1.1 Ancillary Services: Those services as defined in the OATT that are necessary to support the transmission of electric capacity and energy from resources to loads while maintaining reliable operation of the New England Transmission System in accordance with Good Utility Practice. 1.2 B-CPT-W Eligible Customer: An Electric Storage Facility that exclusively self-dispatches to store electric energy for sale for resale in the New England wholesale energy market that is or will be directly interconnected with Central Maines Distribution System. 1.3 B-ESA Eligible Customer: An Electric Storage Facility that exclusively follows ISO-NE dispatch instructions to provide Ancillary Services that is or will be directly interconnected with Central Maines Distribution System. 1.4 Central Maine (or CMP): The Central Maine Power Company. 1.5 Commission: The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1.6 Demand Charge Rate: A per/kW rate for Distribution Service as set forth in Sections II and III of the Tariff. 1.7 Distribution Customer: Any Eligible Customer that (i) executes a Service Agreement or (ii) requests in writing that the Distribution Provider file with the Commission, a proposed unexecuted Service Agreement to receive Distribution Service pursuant to the terms of the Tariff or (iii) receives Distribution Service from Central Maine whose demand does not exceed 2000 kW. 1.8 Distribution Provider: Central Maine Power Company, the public utility that owns, controls, and operates facilities used for the distribution of electric energy and provides Distribution Service under the Tariff. 1.9 Distribution Service: The wholesale distribution service provided under the Tariff. 1.10 Distribution System: Those non-ISO-NE administered delivery facilities owned, controlled and operated by the Distribution Provider that are used to provide Distribution Service under the Tariff. 1.11 Electric Storage Facility: A storage facility that participates in the New England Markets as described in ISO-NEs market rules. 1.12 Eligible Customer: A B-CPT-W Eligible Customer or a B-ESA Eligible Customer. 1.13 End-Use Customer: A Central Maine customer that takes final delivery of electric power and does not resell the power. 1.14 Good Utility Practice: Any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather includes all acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region, including those practices required by Federal Power Act Section 215(a)(4). 1.15 ISO-NE: The New England Independent System Operator, or any successor organization or entity, responsible for the continued operation of the New England Control Area and the administration of the Tariff, subject to regulation by the Commission. ISO-NE is a nonprofit corporation that controls certain transmission facilities of all Participating TOs and dispatches certain generating units and loads. 1.16 ISO Tariff: The ISO New England Inc. Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff, as it may be modified from time to time, and accepted by the Commission. 1.17 Local Network Service (LNS): Local transmission service provided by Central Maine pursuant to Schedule 21 and Schedule 21-CMP. 1.18 New England Transmission System: The system of transmission facilities, including PTF and Non-PTF, under ISO-NEs operational jurisdiction. 1.19 Open Access Transmission Tariff (OATT): Section II of the ISO New England Inc. Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff, as it may be modified from time to time, and accepted by the Commission. 1.20 Participating Transmission Owner (TO): A transmission owner that is a party to the TOA. 1.21 Parties: The Distribution Provider and the Distribution Customer receiving service under the Tariff. 1.22 Pool Transmission Facility (PTF): The transmission facilities owned by PTOs which meet the criteria specified in the OATT. 1.23 Regional Network Service (RNS): The transmission service over the PTF described in the OATT. 1.24 Service Agreement: The initial agreement and any amendments or supplements thereto entered into by the Distribution Customer and the Distribution Provider for service under the Tariff. 1.25 Tariff: This Wholesale Distribution Access Tariff. 1.26 Transmission Operating Agreement (TOA): The Transmission Operating Agreement between and among ISO-NE and the PTOs, as amended and restated from time to time. 1.27 Transmission Service: The transmission service provided over PTF under the terms and conditions of the OATT, designated as Regional Network Service, and over Central Maines Local Network (Non-PTF), designated as Local Network Service or Local Point-To-Point Service that is provided pursuant to Schedule 21 and Schedule 21-CMP. 1.28 Transmission System: The facilities owned, controlled or operated by Central Maine that are used to provide Transmission Service under the OATT, Schedule 21 and Schedule 21-CMP. Central Maines Transmission System consists of two parts: (1) those transmission facilities which qualify as PTF in accordance with the OATT and (2) those remaining transmission facilities which constitute Central Maines Local Network. 2. Ancillary Services Ancillary Services are needed with Transmission Service to maintain reliability within the New England Control Area. Ancillary Services are not available in or through this Tariff. This Tariff does provide a wholesale distribution rate for Electric Storage Facilities interconnected to the Distribution System providing Ancillary Services to the ISO-NE wholesale market. 3. Billing and Payment 3.1 Billing Procedure Within a reasonable time after the first day of each month, Central Maine shall submit an invoice to the Distribution Customer for the charges for all services furnished under this Tariff during the preceding month. The invoice shall be paid by the Distribution Customer within ten (10) days of receipt. All payments shall be made, in accordance with the procedure specified by Central Maine in immediately available funds payable to Central Maine, or by wire transfer to a bank named by Central Maine. 3.2 Customer Default In the event the Distribution Customer fails, for any reason other than a billing dispute as described below, to make payment to Central Maine on or before the due date as described above, and such failure of payment is not corrected within thirty (30) calendar days after Central Maine notifies the Distribution Customer to cure such failure, or if the Distribution Customer violates any provision of this Tariff or its Service Agreement, a default by the Distribution Customer shall be deemed to exist. Upon the occurrence of a default, Central Maine may initiate a proceeding with the Commission to terminate service but shall not terminate service until the Commission so approves any such request. In the event of a billing dispute between Central Maine and the Distribution Customer, Central Maine will continue to provide service pursuant to the Tariff and any Service Agreement hereunder as long as the Distribution Customer (i) continues to make all payments not in dispute, and (ii) pays into an independent escrow account the portion of the invoice in dispute, pending resolution of such dispute. If the Distribution Customer fails to meet these two requirements for continuation of service, then Central Maine may provide notice to the Distribution Customer of its intention to suspend service in sixty (60) days, and may proceed with such suspension. 3.3 Rate Election A Distribution Customer taking service under this Tariff may elect to switch between the rates contained in this Tariff (i.e., the B-CPT-W rate and the B-ESA rate), provided the Distribution Customer meets the eligibility requirements of the rate. Switching between the rates may not be made at shorter intervals than twelve months. 4. Force Majeure and Indemnification 4.1 Force Majeure An event of Force Majeure means any act of God, labor disturbance, act of the public enemy, war, insurrection, riot, fire, storm or flood, explosion, breakage or accident to machinery or equipment, any Curtailment, any order, regulation or restriction imposed by a court or governmental military or lawfully established civilian authorities, or any other cause beyond a partys control. Neither Central Maine nor the Distribution Customer will be considered in default as to any obligation under or related to this Tariff if prevented from fulfilling the obligation due to an event of Force Majeure; provided that no event of Force Majeure shall excuse any payment obligation hereunder or under a Service Agreement. However, a party whose performance under or related to this Tariff is hindered by an event of Force Majeure shall make all reasonable efforts to perform its obligations under or related to this Tariff, and shall promptly notify Central Maine or the Distribution Customer, whichever is appropriate, of the commencement and end of each event of Force Majeure. 4.2 Indemnification The Distribution Customer shall at all times indemnify, defend, and save Central Maine harmless from, any and all damages, losses, claims, including claims and actions relating to injury to or death of any person or damage to property, demands, suits, recoveries, costs and expenses, court costs, attorney fees, and all other obligations by or to third parties, arising out of or resulting from Central Maines performance of its obligations under or related to this Tariff on behalf of the Distribution Customer or resulting from the Distribution Customers acts or omissions under or related to this Tariff, except to the extent that Central Maine is found liable for gross negligence or intentional wrongdoing. For the purposes of this Section, the term third parties includes without limitation, customers under the Tariff, ISO-NE and any other Transmission Owners. 4.3 Limitations of Liability Central Maine shall not be liable (whether based on contract, indemnification, warranty, tort, strict liability or otherwise) for money damages or other compensation to the Distribution Customer for actions or omissions by Central Maine in performing its obligations under or related to this Tariff, or any Service Agreement hereunder, except to the extent that Central Maine is found liable for gross negligence or intentional misconduct and, in which case, Central Maine shall be liable for only actual direct damages. To the extent the Distribution Customer has claims against Central Maine, the Distribution Customer may only look to the assets of Central Maine for the enforcement of such claims and may not seek to enforce any claims against the Affiliates of Central Maine or the respective directors, members, officers, employees or agents of Central Maine or any of its Affiliates who the Distribution Customer acknowledges and agrees have no personal or other liability for obligations of Central Maine by reason of their status as Affiliates or directors, members, officers, employees or agents of Central Maine or any of its Affiliates. In no event shall Central Maine be liable for any incidental, consequential, multiple, punitive, special, exemplary, or indirect damages, or loss of revenues or profits, attorneys fees or costs arising out of, or connected in any way with the performance or non-performance of this Tariff or any Service Agreement hereunder, even if such damages are foreseeable or the damaged party has advised Central Maine of the possibility of such damages and regardless of whether any such damages are deemed to result from the failure or inadequacy of any exclusive or other remedy. 4.4 Survival The provisions of this Section 4 survive termination or expiration of this Tariff or a Service Agreement hereunder. 5. Creditworthiness For the purpose of determining the ability of the Distribution Customer to meet its obligations related to service hereunder, Central Maine may require reasonable credit review procedures in accordance with Attachment L of Schedule 21-CMP, wherein Distribution Customer shall be treated as a Transmission Customer and often referred to as Customer for purposes of Attachment L. 6. Dispute Resolution Procedures 6.1 Internal Dispute Resolution Procedures Any dispute between a Distribution Customer and Central Maine involving Distribution Service under this Tariff (excluding applications for rate changes or other changes to this Tariff, or to any Service Agreement entered into under this Tariff, which shall be presented directly to the Commission for resolution) shall be referred to a designated senior representative of Central Maine and a senior representative of the Distribution Customer for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the dispute within thirty (30) days or such other period as the parties may agree upon by mutual agreement, such dispute may be submitted to mediation or arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth in Section I.6 of the ISO Tariff. 6.2 Rights Under the Federal Power Act Nothing in this section shall restrict the rights of any party to file a complaint with the Commission or seek any other available remedy under relevant provisions of the Federal Power Act. 7. Governing Law Except as otherwise provided by federal law, this Tariff shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the state of Maine.
